Intake-2021: Finance

  • Summary
  • Solving
    • Method 1 - reversing
    • Method 2 - Enabling macros
      • Debugging code
    • Decrypting the new code

Summary

Finance was another forensics challenge that I made for the beginner ctf “IntakeCTF”. It was a simple word document that had a malicious macro inside. There were a couple of ways to solve it but the main difficulty was that the malicious code had been p-stomped/vba-stomped.

Solving

Starting with the initial file

We know this is malicious so we can take a look at the macros that accompany the document by going to: Developer->Visual Basic (if the developer tab is not available), go to file->options->customize ribbon-> tick the developer box.

We can now see code:

All it appears to do is run ipconfig, tree and echo. Which doesn’t do anything malicious. There is a mention of pseudo-code which is strange given the current code is visual basic. After some googling, there is mention of pseudo-code on wikipedia.

Microsoft has an intermediate language called P-Code. This appears to be a document that’s been p-stomped.

There are a few slightly different ways of recovering the code embedded in the document

Method 1 - reversing

From the article, I can recover the p-code with pcodedmp. When I do so, I get a huge output:

Looking near the top, we can see:

Where we can see a string LitStr... and then a StrRev and finally a St, LitStr likely means literal string. StrRev could be assumed to reverse the string or can be seen in the p-code:

And then st will store it in a variable named YlkEdVZY. This is later base64 decoded: before writing to a file %USERPROFILE%\Downloads\TimeSeries.csproj; Built with msbuild and then executed with ShellExecute

Note: TimeSeries.csproj will be the file name To reverse the base64, I first filter out the junk by regex searching for LitStr.* and then remove everything but the base64 by replacing the regex (LitStr 0x00C8 |") with nothing. Then reverse the string on each line (remember the StrRev) before merging the lines together and finally base64 decoding it. This process can be seen on this cyberchef link.

Method 2 - Enabling macros

If using this method, it’s advisable to run in a virtual/isolated environment so that if this sample is truly malicious, it would not affect anything else on the network or on the device.

However, after clicking the enable content button:

And then going back into the visual basic editor, the code has changed:

The base64 strings that were seen in the previous method can also be seen here. These can once again be decrypted in the same way.

Debugging code

Alternatively, instead of decoding, the debugger can be used to get the output. The compiled code would be executed with the ShellExecute:

The file can be seen in the Open Environ( function since it gets the filename using the %USERPROFILE% environment variable and then the Print #1, decodeBase64( to decode and then print the contents into that file. There’s also a Kill Environ( which deletes a file. So between creation and deletion of the file, the contents are executed with the command listed in ShellExecute. The # don’t offer much obfuscation and they’re just removed anyway so they mean nothing. However, we can set a breakpint on the shellexecute and the file at that point should still exist and the contents can be read:

When running with the play button in the editor, and sure enough, when the program breaks, a file is present in the downloads directory.

Decrypting the new code

As seen in the picture, c# code can be found. It’s all on one line but new lines can be added wherever a ; is seen since that’s what c# uses as a delimiter:

using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Diagnostics;
using System.Reflection;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;
using System.Collections.ObjectModel;
using System.Management.Automation;
using System.Management.Automation.Runspaces;
using System.Text;using Microsoft.Build.Framework;
using Microsoft.Build.Utilities;
public class ClassExample:Task,ITask{
    public override bool Execute(){
        Program.Main();
        return true;
    }
}
    public class Program{
        public static void Main(){
            byte[]data=Convert.FromBase64String("big chunk of b64 here");
            string script=Encoding.Unicode.GetString(data);
            Runspace r=RunspaceFactory.CreateRunspace();
            r.Open();
            Pipeline p=r.CreatePipeline();
            p.Commands.AddScript(script);
            p.InvokeAsync();
        }
    }

Once again, the base64 can be decoded to see:

So the first command does nothing of interest but there’s another encoded command. Powershell encoded command’s appear to be base64 however a regular base64 decode doesn’t work. This is because powershell encodedcommands are base64 emcpded with UTF-16LE. This can be decoded in a few ways but a basic online tool gets the job done, producing:

The script is a reverse shell, it does not get executed instantly since it’s defining a function, going through the code, right at the bottom is the reverse shell trigger:

which is the flag!
